<br>
I'd like to try to inject a little reality into what has been said though.  This is based on my own history playing on Povar since Nov. 1999.  <br>
<br>
To start off with, before Kunark, the level cap was 50.  There is no denying that.  The problem is that both articles are looking through rose colored glasses and saying things that are untrue.  <br>
<br>
The fact is that the game is one that demands a time commitment, even as a casual player.  I played casually.  <br>
<br>
When I would log in with my RL friend after she got me into the game.  We'd play for hours, though I would play a bit extra because she started before I did and I wanted to catch up.  We'd save up our coppers and sold every bit we could scavenge from the corpses, and each time one of us leveled, we'd meet on the ground near the orc lift and work our  way through a stack of mead and it was a blast.  <br>
<br>
Then I got to level 12, and we both got into a guild.  <br>
<br>
Even in those days, if you wanted &quot;the good stuff&quot;, you had to camp it.  For hours or days on end.  People complained back then about it too, but now they seem to have forgotten the permanent camps in places like lguk for the DE mask or the AC (croc or cyclops) and stuff like that.  There was a time sink even then, and no one would accept the idea that you should be able to progress through dungeons, and just happen to find creatures up and kill them and maybe get the loot you wanted.  No, you had to camp it.  <br>
<br>
If you wanted the &quot;uber&quot; stuff, like dragon kills or going to hate or fear, you needed to be in a guild in order to do it.  Those spots were not available to the casual player.  The big guilds always hit those spots.  Raiding was in the game when the dragons were in.  Welcome to &quot;uber&quot; content, stuff that needed organized guilds.   <br>
<br>
The guild I was in (lore keepers) had a lot of high level peeps, but it split and formed an uber guild with some other folks, a guild that had level requirements to get in, and one that was specifically raid oriented. (nightmare's asylum)  I liked the guild I was in, so I stayed with it.  Peeps that I was friends with that had moved on would talk to me and tell me about stuff that dropped.  But if I wanted to get that stuff, I had to leave the guild I was in and join them (as well as spending the time to level).  I was more into having fun. <br>
<br>
When Kunark came out, I was in my low 30's, and grouping in cazic and just enjoying the game. <br>
<br>
Kunark it was more of the same.  A whole bunch of stuff for regular players, and some content that was raid only, like the dragons and stuff.  the epics were added later, and those were mostly ubers only too.  The casual players were gaining levels and joining the big guilds, or staying with their old guilds and hitting the old world content that was now available to them because of their new power (and the fact that the big guilds had moved on).  The time sink remained in the game because you still had to sit and camp stuff for hours on end, and a new very specific time sink got added with the key to VP.  You had a time sink AND a big guild raid only target (trakanon) required to get into this one zone.   Very few peeps got there.  <br>
<br>
I was still in my 30's when the next expansion came out.  I didn't want to just focus on grinding out levels (boring!), I was still having fun, doing quests and starting alts and seeing what they could do etc.  I was still having a blast with the game.  <br>
<br>
Next came Velious, once again, you had time sinks (mass slaughter for faction), more restricted content (sleepers tomb) and stuff that only the ubers could hit, while the casual players could now hit the content from kunark when they got the upgrades from the new content.   They also introduced progressive quests, which were pretty spiffy in and of themselves, but required a large time commitment and the end rewards needed the uber guilds to do.  <br>
<br>
When velious came out, I got the expansion the first day, I took the boat over, and ran around in the snow fields and looked at the bunnies and marveled at the other cool graphics.  Then I left and didn't come back for months.  <br>
<br>
By that time, friends had all leveled past me, and I decided it was time to level.   I did that to the exclusion of all else, and the camps in the old worlds were now open, so I could level fast without all the competition.  After kiting for a couple of weeks, I'd gained levels, and I went to my first dragon raid the day I hit 46.  It was a pickup raid and I won Selo's drums and was so very psyched.  <br>
<br>
So, as a casual player, I was now hitting older content with other casual players, and it was all good as far as I was concerned.  I wanted the cool gear, but I wasn't in a big guild, so I wasn't going to get it.  I was getting other stuff that I hadn't had the opportunity to get because I wasn't in an uber guild.  My original guild had died, and I had joined a family type guild. <br>
<br>
Then came Luclin.  Again, more of the same, a lot of content for the casual player, with new stuff that required keys to get into.  This meant that the uber guilds still had something to  do, and there were still time sinks, and those of us that were casual now had more content (velious) that we could hit because of our power gains in luclin (new spells etc.).  <br>
<br>
I did hit 60 before the next expansion, but again, that's because I finally focused on leveling to the exclusion of all else.  It was grinding exp day in and day out for long periods of time.  It required a time commitment.  <br>
<br>
Then came PoP, which a lot of peeps referred to as the end when things fell apart.  I couldn't disagree more.  If you wanted access to the new content, then you had to be geared decently with the old content (epics or better, velious armors etc).  The casual/family guilds could get past the trials to get into PoV and PoS, it just took a lot of time (and some luck), LIKE EVERYTHING ELSE IN THE GAME UP TIL THEN!  <br>
<br>
You also had the option to do quests to get you into some of the other zones, and those quests took time, but were very doable by a single group. <br>
<br>
But Verant listened to the complaints and opened up the lower tiers of the expansion based on level.  And that's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>still</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> not good enough because the casual players don't have access to the higher raid content without doing the lower raids.   <br>
<br>
They complain that they should have the same opportunity to do/see the content as the ubers do because they pay the same amount of money.  They do this without taking the time to think that they <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>DO</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> have the same opportunity to do/see content as the ubers, but they are not able (for whatever reason) to devote the time to do this<br>
<br>
I finally decided that I wanted to see some of the spots I hadn't seen before, and I joined a raiding guild.  I'm not quite elemental flagged (need RZ), but I'm almost time flagged, and I have been piggy-backed into the elemental planes several times and I think that's cool.  <br>
<br>
There's also a loose organization of small guilds and unguilded peeps that are doing flag raids to get others into the higher planes, and that's great.  <br>
<br>
I've been to a bunch of these raids, and they do fail a lot of the time because the game does require a time commitment (whether you are willing to beleive it or not) and it does require that you pay attention and listen to those that are more experienced.  If you don't, you wipe out and peeps don't get the flags.  And a  lot of the times when things are starting to go bad (or have gone bad and the organizers want to make another run now that peeps know better), a lot of the casual players start to bail out because they don't have another hour or two to try again for whatever reason.  And then they complain that they can't get into the planes. <br>
<br>
I don't know how much of this makes sense, but I hope I made some kind of point. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=456989" target="top">Muse Idril Galelin</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->,   <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=860858" target="top">Exarch Mirai Tekk'sint</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=idrilgalelin>Idril Galelin</A> at: 6/2/04 2:39 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=frostdragonsinger@theconcerthall>FrostDragonsinger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Minstrel</span><br>  Posts: 66<br> <font color=#330000>(6/2/04 1:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallbackstage.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19439.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> agreed</span><hr size=1> Very good Idril, You hit it well <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   GO POVAR<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
